# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: homebrew
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:homebrew/docs-brew-sh] Start with installation, `man brew`, troubleshooting and FAQ (Frequently Asked Questions) guides if you are new to Homebrew.
[src:homebrew/docs-brew-sh] Documentation is grouped below by audience: users, contributors, maintainers and those interested in Homebrew’s governance.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] A *formula* is a package definition written in Ruby.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] It can be created with `brew create <URL>` where `<URL>` is a zip or tarball, installed with `brew install <formula>`, and debugged with `brew install --debug --verbose <formula>`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Formulae use the `Formula` class API which provides various Homebrew-specific helpers.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Homebrew uses Git for storing formulae and contributing to the project.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] As of Homebrew 4.0.0, formulae are downloaded as JSON from https://formulae.brew.sh which is automatically regenerated by a scheduled Homebrew/formulae.brew.sh job from the default branch of the Homebrew/homebrew-core repository.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Homebrew installs formulae to the Cellar at `$(brew --cellar)` and then symlinks some of the installation into the prefix at `$(brew --prefix)` (e.g.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `/opt/homebrew`) so that other programs can see what’s going on.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] We suggest running `brew ls` on a few of the kegs in your Cellar to see how it is all arranged.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Packages are installed according to their formulae.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `brew edit etl` (or etl.rb) or a more advanced one, e.g.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Make sure you run `brew update` before you start.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This ensures your Homebrew installation is a Git repository.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] To create or edit formulae locally, you’ll need to first tap `homebrew/core` if you haven’t previously.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This clones the Homebrew/homebrew-core Git repository to `$(brew --repository homebrew/core)`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] As you’re developing, you’ll also need to set `HOMEBREW_NO_INSTALL_FROM_API=1` in your shell environment or before any `install`, `reinstall` or `upgrade` commands to force `brew` to use the local repository instead of the API.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Before submitting a new formula make sure you read over our contribution guidelines.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This creates `$(brew --repository)/Library/Taps/homebrew/homebrew-core/Formula/f/foo.rb` and opens it in your `EDITOR`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Passing in `--ruby` or `--python` will populate various defaults commonly useful for projects written in those languages.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If `brew` said `Warning: Version cannot be determined from URL` when doing the `create` step, you’ll need to explicitly add the correct `version` to the formula and then save the formula.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Homebrew will try to guess the formula’s name from its URL.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If it fails to do so you can override this with `brew create <URL> --set-name <name>`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] An SSL/TLS (https) `homepage` is preferred, if one is available.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Try to summarise from the `homepage` what the formula does in the `desc`ription.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Note that the `desc`ription is automatically prepended with the formula name when printed.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] We only accept formulae that use a Debian Free Software Guidelines license or are released into the public domain following DFSG Guidelines on Public Domain software.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Use the license identifier from the SPDX License List e.g.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `license "BSD-2-Clause"`, or use `license :public_domain` for public domain software.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Use `:any_of`, `:all_of` or `:with` to describe complex license expressions.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `:any_of` should be used when the user can choose which license to use.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `:all_of` should be used when the user must use all licenses.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `:with` should be used to specify a valid SPDX exception.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Add `+` to an identifier to indicate that the formulae can be licensed under later versions of the same license.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Check out the License Guidelines for examples of complex license expressions in Homebrew formulae.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] You’re now at a new prompt with the tarball extracted to a temporary sandbox.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Does the package install with `./configure`, `cmake`, or something else?
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Delete the commented out `cmake` lines if the package uses `./configure`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] The `README` probably tells you about dependencies and Homebrew or macOS probably already has them.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] You can check for Homebrew dependencies with `brew search`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] There are plenty of others; check `/usr/lib` for them.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] We generally try not to duplicate system libraries and complicated tools in core Homebrew but we do duplicate some commonly used tools.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Special exceptions are OpenSSL and LibreSSL.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Things that use either *should* be built using Homebrew’s shipped equivalent and our BrewTestBot’s post-install `audit` will warn if it detects you haven’t done this.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] For `Homebrew/homebrew-core`, keep dependencies minimal and context-dependent.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Prefer dependencies needed to build, test or satisfy current core dependents, and avoid adding optional upstream features that bring in large recursive dependency trees.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] When a formula needs both a light default build and a maximal build, maintainers may prefer a separate `*-full` formula instead.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] See the dependency policy in the `Homebrew/homebrew-core` Maintainer Guide.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `"jpeg"`) specifies a formula dependency.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `:xcode`) specifies a `Requirement` to restrict installation to systems meeting certain criteria, which can be fulfilled by one or more formulae, casks or other system-wide installed software (e.g.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Some `Requirement`s can also take a string or symbol specifying their minimum version that the formula depends on.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Top-level `depends_on :macos` marks a formula as macOS-only.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Top-level `depends_on macos: :sonoma` marks a formula as macOS-only and declares the minimum compatible macOS release.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Top-level `depends_on maximum_macos: :ventura` marks a formula as macOS-only and declares the newest compatible macOS release.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Top-level `depends_on :linux` marks a formula as Linux-only.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] For a formula that supports both macOS and Linux but needs a specific macOS version, put the macOS version requirement inside `on_macos`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Sometimes there’s a hard conflict between formulae that can’t be avoided or circumvented with `keg_only`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] A good example for minor conflict is the `mbedtls` formula, which ships and compiles a “Hello World” executable.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This is obviously non-essential to `mbedtls`’s functionality, and as conflict with the popular GNU `hello` formula would be overkill, we just remove it during the installation process.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `pdftohtml` provides an example of a serious conflict, where each listed formula ships an identically named binary that is essential to functionality, so a `conflicts_with` is preferable.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] As a general rule, `conflicts_with` should be a last-resort option.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] In Homebrew we sometimes accept formulae updates that don’t include a version bump.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] These include resource updates, new patches or fixing a security issue with a formula.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Occasionally, these updates require a forced-recompile of the formula itself or its dependents to either ensure formulae continue to function as expected or to close a security issue.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This forced-recompile is known as a `revision` and is inserted underneath the `homepage`/`url`/`sha256`/`license` block.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] When a dependent of a formula fails to build against a new version of that dependency it must receive a `revision`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] An example of such failure is in this issue report and its fix.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `revision`s are also used for formulae that move from the system OpenSSL to the Homebrew-shipped OpenSSL without any other changes to that formula.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This ensures users aren’t left exposed to the potential security issues of the outdated OpenSSL.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] An example of this can be seen in this commit.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Use `compatibility_version` to record whether a formula update remains compatible with already-built dependents.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Homebrew records this in installed tabs so later installs and upgrades can avoid rebuilding dependents unnecessarily when the installed dependency is still known to be compatible.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This exists both to reduce the number of dependency upgrades users need and to avoid unnecessary dependent `revision` bumps.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Bump `compatibility_version` by `1` when a formula update requires any recursive dependent formula to receive a `revision` bump in the same pull request.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If only some dependents need rebuilding, still bump `compatibility_version`; only the dependents that actually need rebuilding should receive a `revision` bump.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Do not change `compatibility_version` for updates that do not require dependent `revision` bumps.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] It should never decrease and should only increment by `1` at a time.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Use `brew bump-compatibility-version` to increment `compatibility_version` mechanically.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `brew audit` checks this relationship in both directions.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If a formula’s `compatibility_version` increases, at least one recursive dependent in the same pull request must also increase `revision` by `1`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If a formula’s `revision` increases because a changed recursive dependency also changed versions, that dependency must increase `compatibility_version` by `1`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] These checks are based on dependent `revision` bumps in the pull request, not on general ABI analysis.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Homebrew cannot automatically detect every compatibility break that is not covered by linkage or formula tests, so maintainers may still need to bump `compatibility_version` and dependent `revision`s manually when they know a rebuild is required.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Sometimes formulae have version schemes that change such that a direct comparison between two versions no longer produces the correct result.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] For example, a project might be version `13` and then decide to become `1.0.0`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] As `13` is translated to `13.0.0` by our versioning system by default this requires intervention.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] When a version scheme of a formula fails to recognise a new version as newer it must receive a `version_scheme`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] An example of this can be seen in this pull request.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] When you already have a lot of formulae installed, it’s easy to miss a common dependency.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If a formula dependency is required on all platforms but can be handled by a component that ships with macOS, specify it with `uses_from_macos`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] On Linux it acts like `depends_on`, while on macOS it’s ignored unless the host system is older than the optional `since:` parameter.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Homebrew doesn’t package already-packaged language-specific libraries.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] These should be installed directly from `gem`/`cpan`/`pip` etc.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] The preferred mechanism for installing gem dependencies is to use `bundler` with the upstream’s `Gemfile.lock`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This requires the upstream checks in their `Gemfile.lock`, so if they don’t, it’s a good idea to file an issue and ask them to do so.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] For python we use `resource`s for dependencies and there’s automation to generate these for you.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Running `brew update-python-resources <formula>` will automatically add the necessary `resource` stanzas for the dependencies of your Python application to the formula.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Note that `brew update-python-resources` is run automatically by `brew create` if you pass the `--python` switch.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If `brew update-python-resources` is unable to determine the correct `resource` stanzas, homebrew-pypi-poet is a good third-party alternative that may help.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If all else fails, you’ll want to use `resource`s for all other language-specific dependencies.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This requires you to specify both a specific URL for a version and the sha256 checksum for security.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `jrnl` is an example of a formula that does this well.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] The end result means the user doesn’t have to use `pip` or Python and can just run `jrnl`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `--debug` will ask you to open an interactive shell if the build fails so you can try to figure out what went wrong.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Some configure scripts do not recognise e.g.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If you see a warning about it, remove the option from the formula.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Add a valid test to the `test do` block of the formula.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This will be run by `brew test foo` and BrewTestBot.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] The `test do` block automatically creates and changes to a temporary directory which is deleted after run.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] You can access this `Pathname` with the `testpath` function.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] The environment variable `HOME` is set to `testpath` within the `test do` block.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] We want tests that don’t require any user input and test the basic functionality of the application.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] For example `foo build-foo input.foo` is a good test and (despite their widespread use) `foo --version` and `foo --help` are bad tests.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] However, a bad test is better than no test at all.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] See the `cmake` formula for an example of a good test.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] It writes a basic `CMakeLists.txt` file into the test directory then calls CMake to generate Makefiles.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This test checks that CMake doesn’t e.g. segfault during basic operation.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Homebrew expects to find manual pages in `#{prefix}/share/man/...`, and not in `#{prefix}/man/...`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Some software installs to `man` instead of `share/man`, so check the output and add a `"--mandir=#{man}"` to the `./configure` line if needed.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] In case there are specific issues with the Homebrew packaging (compared to how the software is installed from other sources) a `caveats` block can be added to the formula to warn users.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Name the formula like the project markets the product.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] So it’s `pkgconf`, not `pkgconfig`; `sdl_mixer`, not `sdl-mixer` or `sdlmixer`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] The only exception is stuff like “Apache Ant”.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Apache sticks “Apache” in front of everything, but we use the formula name `ant`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] We only include the prefix in cases like `gnuplot` (because it’s part of the name) and `gnu-go` (because everyone calls it “GNU Go”—nobody just calls it “Go”).
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] The word “Go” is too common and there are too many implementations of it.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If you’re not sure about the name, check its homepage, Wikipedia page and what Debian calls it.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] When Homebrew already has a formula called `foo` we typically do not accept requests to replace that formula with something else also named `foo`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This is to avoid both confusing and surprising users’ expectations.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] When two formulae share an upstream name, e.g.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] AESCrypt and AES Crypt the newer formula must typically adapt its name to avoid conflict with the current formula.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If you’re *still* not sure, just commit.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] We’ll apply some arbitrary rule and make a decision 😉.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] When importing classes, Homebrew will require the formula and then create an instance of the class.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] It does this by assuming the formula name can be directly converted to the class name using a `regexp`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Thus, if you change the name of the class, you must also rename the file.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Filenames should be all lowercase, and class names should be the strict CamelCase equivalent, e.g. formulae `gnu-go` and `sdl_mixer` become classes `GnuGo` and `SdlMixer`, even if part of their name is an acronym.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Add aliases by creating symlinks in an `Aliases` directory in the tap root.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] You can run `brew audit --strict --online` to test formulae for adherence to Homebrew house style, which is loosely based on the Ruby Style Guide.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] The `audit` command includes warnings for trailing whitespace, preferred URLs for certain source hosts, and many other style issues.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Fixing these warnings before committing will make the process a lot quicker for everyone.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] New formulae being submitted to Homebrew should run `brew audit --new --formula foo`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This command is performed by BrewTestBot on new submissions as part of the automated build and test process, and highlights more potential issues than the standard audit.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Use `brew info` and check if the version guessed by Homebrew from the URL is correct.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] At Homebrew, we require the name of the formula up front like so: `foobar 7.3 (new formula)`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This may seem crazy short, but you’ll find that forcing yourself to summarise the commit encourages you to be atomic and concise.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If you can’t summarise it in 50 to 80 characters, you’re probably trying to commit two commits as one.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] For a more thorough explanation, please read Tim Pope’s excellent blog post, A Note About Git Commit Messages.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] The required commit message format for simple version updates is `foobar 7.3` and for fixes is `foobar: fix flibble matrix.`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Please squash your commits into one with this message format, otherwise your PR will be replaced by our autosquash workflow.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Ensure you reference any relevant GitHub issue, e.g.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Homebrew’s history is the first thing future contributors will look to when trying to understand the current state of formulae they’re interested in.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Now you just need to push your commit to GitHub.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If you haven’t forked Homebrew yet, go to the Homebrew/homebrew-core repository and hit the Fork button.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Now, open a pull request for your changes.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Use `odie` when you need to exit a formula gracefully for any reason.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] For any formula using certain well-known build systems, there will be arguments that should be passed during compilation so that the build conforms to Homebrew standards.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] These have been collected into a set of `std_*_args` methods.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Detailed information about each of those methods can be found in the `Formula` class API documentation.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Most of these methods accept parameters to customize their output.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] It also provides a convenient way to set `-ldflags`, `-gcflags`, and `-tags`, see examples: `babelfish` and `wazero` formulae.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `release_mode` is a symbol that accepts only `:fast`, `:safe`, and `:small` values (with `:fast` being default).
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] You’ll see stuff like this in some formulae.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This moves the file `foo` into the formula’s `bin` directory (`/opt/homebrew/Cellar/pkg/0.1/bin`) and makes it executable (`chmod 0555 foo`).
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Variables for the most common directory locations are available.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] You can also rename the file during the installation process.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This can be useful for adding a prefix to binaries that would otherwise cause conflicts with another formula, or for removing a file extension.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `inreplace` is a convenience function that can edit files in-place.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `before` and `after` can be strings or regular expressions.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `inreplace` should be used instead of patches when patching something that will never be accepted upstream, e.g. making the software’s build system respect Homebrew’s installation hierarchy.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If it’s something that affects both Homebrew and MacPorts (i.e. macOS specific) it should be turned into an upstream submitted patch instead.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Note that values *can* contain unescaped spaces if you use the multiple-argument form of `system`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] While `patch`es should generally be avoided, sometimes they are temporarily necessary.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] When `patch`ing (i.e. fixing header file inclusion, fixing compiler warnings, etc.) the first thing to do is check whether the upstream project is aware of the issue.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] If not, file a bug report and/or submit your patch for inclusion.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] We may sometimes still accept your patch before it was submitted upstream but by getting the ball rolling on fixing the upstream issue you reduce the length of time we have to carry the patch around.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `patch`es can be declared in `stable` and `head` blocks.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Always use a block instead of a conditional, i.e.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `stable do ... end` instead of `if build.stable? then ... end`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Patches can also be embedded by passing a string.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] This makes it possible to provide multiple embedded patches while making only some of them conditional.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] In embedded and external patches, the string “@@HOMEBREW_PREFIX@@” is replaced with the value of the constant `HOMEBREW_PREFIX` before the patch is applied.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] External and `file` patches can optionally declare a `type` and what they `resolve`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] These annotations are exposed in `brew info --json` and the formula API for downstream tools such as SBOM generators and vulnerability scanners; they have no effect on how the patch is applied.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `type` describes where the patch came from, using the `pedigree.patches` terminology from the CycloneDX specification.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `:backport` takes code from a newer version of the same software and applies it to the older version Homebrew ships.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `:cherry_pick` selectively applies an upstream commit that is *not* from a strictly newer release line, such as a fix that only exists on a maintenance or release branch.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] When in doubt between `:backport` and `:cherry_pick`, prefer `:backport` for anything taken from the upstream development tip.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `:unofficial` is a patch not authored by the upstream maintainers, such as a Homebrew- or distribution-specific build fix.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] As with all Homebrew patches, an `:unofficial` patch should have been reported and/or submitted upstream where practical.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] `resolves` records what the patch fixes: one or more CVE identifiers (`CVE-YYYY-NNNN`), GHSA identifiers (`GHSA-xxxx-xxxx-xxxx`) or issue/PR URLs.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] CVE identifiers are also inferred automatically from the patch `url`, `apply` paths and `file` path, so a Debian-style `CVE-2016-2399.patch` is picked up without an explicit `resolves`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Now just paste into the formula after `__END__`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p01] Instead of `git diff | pbcopy`, for some editors `git diff >> path/to/your/formula/foo.rb` might help you ensure that the patch is not altered, e.g. whitespace removal, indentation changes, etc.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] See the `Formula` class API documentation for the full list of methods available within a formula.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] If anything isn’t clear, you can usually figure it out by `grep`ping the `$(brew --repository homebrew/core)` directory for examples.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Please submit a pull request to amend this document if you think it will help!
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Often, formulae need different dependencies, resources, patches, conflicts, deprecations or `keg_only` statuses on different OSes and architectures.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] In these cases, the components can be nested inside `on_macos`, `on_linux`, `on_arm` or `on_intel` blocks.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Components can also be declared for specific macOS versions or version ranges.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] For example, to declare a dependency only on Sequoia, nest the `depends_on` call inside an `on_sequoia` block.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Add an `:or_older` or `:or_newer` parameter to the `on_sequoia` method to add the dependency to all macOS versions that meet the condition.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Sometimes, a dependency is needed on certain macOS versions *and* on Linux.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] To check multiple conditions, nest the corresponding blocks.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Inside `def install` and `test do`, don’t use these `on_*` methods.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] See the `icoutils` formula for an example.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] When `brew livecheck` is unable to identify versions for a formula, we can control its behavior using a `livecheck` block.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] For `url`/`regex` guidelines and additional `livecheck` block examples, refer to the `brew livecheck` documentation.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] For more technical information on the methods used in a `livecheck` block, please refer to the `Livecheck` class documentation.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] By default, all new formulae in the `Homebrew/homebrew-core` repository are autobumped.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] This means that future updates are handled automatically by Homebrew CI jobs, and contributors do not have to submit pull requests.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Sometimes, we want to exclude a formula from this list, for one reason or another.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] This can be done by adding the `no_autobump!` method in the formula definition; a reason must be provided with the `because:` parameter.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] A complete list of allowed symbols can be found in `NO_AUTOBUMP_REASONS_LIST`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] See our Autobump documentation for more information about the autobump process.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] When parsing a download URL, Homebrew auto-detects the resource type it points to, whether archive (e.g. tarball, zip) or version control repository (e.g.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Git, Subversion, Mercurial) and chooses an appropriate download strategy.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Some strategies can be passed additional options to alter what’s downloaded.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] If not inferable, specify which of Homebrew’s built-in download strategies to use with the `using:` option.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Homebrew offers these anonymous download strategies.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Formulae can specify an alternate download for the upstream project’s development/cutting-edge source (e.g.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] `master`/`main`/`trunk`) using `head`, which can be activated by passing `--HEAD` when installing.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] You can also bundle the URL and any `head`-specific dependencies and resources in a `head do` block.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] You can test whether the `head` is being built with `build.head?` in the `install` method.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Sometimes a package fails to build when using a certain compiler.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Since recent Xcode versions no longer include a GCC compiler we cannot simply force the use of GCC.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Instead, the correct way to declare this is with the `fails_with` DSL method.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] A properly constructed `fails_with` block documents the latest compiler build version known to cause compilation to fail, and the cause of the failure.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] `cause` takes a string, and the use of heredocs is encouraged to improve readability and allow for more comprehensive documentation.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] `fails_with` declarations can be used with any of `:gcc`, `:llvm`, and `:clang`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Homebrew will use this information to select a working compiler (if one is available).
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] When your code in the install function is run, the current working directory is set to the extracted tarball.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Generally we’d rather you were specific about which files or directories need to be installed rather than installing everything.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] to create the directory structure for the manual page location.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] To install man pages into specific locations, use `man1.install "foo.1", "bar.1"`, `man2.install "foo.2"`, etc.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Note that in the context of Homebrew, `libexec` is reserved for private use by the formula and therefore is not symlinked into `HOMEBREW_PREFIX`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] You can use the file utilities provided by Ruby’s `FileUtils`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] These are included in the `Formula` class, so you do not need the `FileUtils.` prefix to use them.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] When creating symlinks, take special care to ensure they are *relative* symlinks.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] This makes it easier to create a relocatable bottle.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] The symlinks created by `install_symlink` are guaranteed to be relative.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] `ln_s` will only produce a relative symlink when given a relative path.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Several other utilities for Ruby’s `Pathname` can simplify some common operations.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Some formulae install executable scripts written in an interpreted language such as Python or Perl.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Homebrew provides a `rewrite_shebang` method to rewrite the shebang of a script.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] This replaces a script’s original interpreter path with the one the formula depends on.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] This guarantees that the correct interpreter is used at execution time.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] This isn’t required if the build system already handles it (e.g. often with `pip` or Perl `ExtUtils::MakeMaker`).
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] For example, the `icdiff` formula uses this utility.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Note that it is necessary to include the utility in the formula; for example with Python one must use `include Language::Python::Shebang`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] `option` names should be prefixed with the words `with` or `without`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] For example, an option to run a test suite should be named `--with-test` or `--with-check` rather than `--test`, and an option to enable a shared library `--with-shared` rather than `--shared` or `--enable-shared`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] See the alternative `ffmpeg` formula for examples.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] `option`s that aren’t `build.with?` or `build.without?` should be deprecated with `deprecated_option`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] See the `wget` formula for a historical example.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Any initialization steps that aren’t necessarily part of the install process can be located in a `post_install` block, such as setup commands or data directory creation.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] This block can be re-run separately with `brew postinstall <formula>`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] For simple file preparation, prefer `post_install_steps`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] These steps are stored in the JSON API and do not require evaluating formula Ruby.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] A `post_install_steps` block may only contain the supported step calls with literal arguments.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] It cannot call the wider formula DSL or arbitrary Ruby code.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] A formula may define either `post_install_steps` or `post_install`, not both.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] `mkdir`, `mkdir_p` and `touch` default to paths relative to `var`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] `move`, `mv`, `move_children`, `symlink`, `ln_s` and `ln_sf` default their source and target paths to `prefix`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Use `base:`, `source_base:` or `target_base:` when a step needs another formula path such as `pkgetc`; use `source_base: :relative` for relative symlink sources.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] `write` creates a default configuration or data file from literal content.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] It defaults to the same base as the other file preparation steps; pass `base:` (such as `base: :etc`) to target another formula path.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] By default `write` does not overwrite an existing file, so user edits are preserved across upgrades; pass `overwrite: true` to always replace the file.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] A trailing newline is appended unless the content already ends with one, so written files end in a newline as POSIX expects.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Content may use a fixed set of `tokens that are expanded at install time so paths are not hardcoded into the JSON API:`, `,`, `,`, `,`, `and`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Any other `` is left verbatim, so literal braces are never rewritten.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Use tokens instead of Ruby interpolation, for example `write "foo.conf", "prefix = ", base: :etc`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] These steps rebuild shared desktop and cache state using Homebrew-owned tools.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] In the above example, the `libressl` formula replaces its stock list of certificates with a symlink to that of the `ca-certificates` formula.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] For example, Ruby 1.9’s gems should be installed to `var/lib/ruby/` so that gems don’t need to be reinstalled when upgrading Ruby.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] You can usually do this with symlink trickery, or (ideally) a configure option.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Another example would be configuration files that should not be overwritten on package upgrades.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] If after installation you find that to-be-persisted configuration files are not copied but instead *symlinked* into `$(brew --prefix)/etc/` from the Cellar, this can often be rectified by passing an appropriate argument to the package’s configure script.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] To find the file we append `.plist` to the `launchd` service name and `.service` to the `systemd` service name internally.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] This table lists the options you can set within a `service` block.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] The `run` or `name` field must be defined inside the service block.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] If `name` is defined without `run`, then Homebrew makes no attempt to change the package-provided service file according these fields.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] The `run` field indicates what command to run, instructs Homebrew to create a service description file using options set in the block, and therefore is required before using fields other than `name` and `require_root`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Environment variables can be set with a hash.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] For the `PATH` there is the helper method `std_service_path_env` which returns `#{HOMEBREW_PREFIX}/bin:#{HOMEBREW_PREFIX}/sbin:/usr/bin:/bin:/usr/sbin:/sbin` so the service can find other `brew`-installed commands.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] The `sockets` method accepts a formatted socket definition as `<type>://<host>:<port>`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Please note that sockets will be accessible on IPv4 and IPv6 addresses by default.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Homebrew has multiple levels of environment variable filtering which affects which variables are available to formulae.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Firstly, the overall environment in which Homebrew runs is filtered to avoid environment contamination breaking from-source builds.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] In particular, this process filters all but a select list of variables, plus allowing any prefixed with `HOMEBREW_`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] The specific implementation is found in `bin/brew`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] The second level of filtering removes sensitive environment variables (such as credentials like keys, passwords or tokens) to prevent malicious subprocesses from obtaining them.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] This has the effect of preventing any such variables from reaching a formula’s Ruby code since they are filtered before it is called.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] The specific implementation is found in the `ENV.clear_sensitive_environment!` method.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] In summary, any environment variables intended for use by a formula need to conform to these filtering rules in order to be available.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] You can set environment variables in a formula’s `install` or `test` blocks using `ENV["VARIABLE_NAME"] = "VALUE"`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] An example can be seen in the `csound` formula.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Environment variables can also be set temporarily using the `with_env` method; any variables defined in the call to that method will be restored to their original values at the end of the block.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] An example can be seen in the `gh` formula.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] The full list can be found in the `SharedEnvExtension` module and `Superenv` module documentation.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] See our Deprecating, Disabling and Removing documentation for more information about how and when to deprecate or disable a formula, cask or Homebrew code.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] When a new version of the software is released, use `brew bump-formula-pr` to automatically update the `url` and `sha256`, remove any `revision` lines, and submit a pull request.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] See our How to Open a Homebrew Pull Request documentation for more information.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Homebrew tries to automatically determine the `version` from the `url` to avoid duplication.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] If the tarball has an unusual name you may need to manually assign the `version`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] If that fixes it, please open an issue with the upstream project so that we can fix it for everyone.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] `superenv` is our “super environment” that isolates builds by removing `/usr/local/bin` and all user `PATH`s that are not essential for the build.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] It does this because user `PATH`s are often full of stuff that breaks builds.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] `superenv` also removes bad flags from the commands passed to `clang`/`gcc` and injects others (for example all `keg_only` dependencies are added to the `-I` and `-L` flags).
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] If in your local Homebrew build of your new formula, you see `Operation not permitted` errors, this will be because your new formula tried to write to the disk outside of your sandbox area.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] This is enforced on macOS by `sandbox-exec`.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Some software requires a Fortran compiler.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] This can be declared by adding `depends_on "gcc"` to a formula.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Packages requiring MPI should use OpenMPI by adding `depends_on "open-mpi"` to the formula, rather than MPICH.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] These packages have conflicts and provide the same standardised interfaces.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Choosing a default implementation and requiring its adoption allows software to link against multiple libraries that rely on MPI without creating unanticipated incompatibilities due to differing MPI runtimes.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Packages requiring BLAS/LAPACK linear algebra interfaces should link to OpenBLAS by adding `depends_on "openblas"` and (if built with CMake) passing `-DBLA_VENDOR=OpenBLAS` to CMake, rather than Apple’s Accelerate framework or the default reference `lapack` implementation.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Apple’s implementation of BLAS/LAPACK is outdated and may introduce hard-to-debug problems.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] The reference `lapack` formula is fine, although it is not actively maintained or tuned.
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] Have you created a real mess in Git which stops you from creating a commit you want to submit to us?
[src:homebrew/formula-cookbook-p02] You might want to consider starting again from scratch.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew has made extensive use of GitHub to expand the support of several packages through user contributions.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] In 2010, Homebrew was the third-most-forked repository on GitHub.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] In 2012, Homebrew had the largest number of new contributors on GitHub.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] In 2013, Homebrew had both the largest number of contributors and issues closed of any project on GitHub.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew has spawned several sub-projects such as Linuxbrew, a Linux port now officially merged into Homebrew; Homebrew Cask, which builds upon Homebrew and focuses on the installation of GUI applications; and "taps" dedicated to specific areas or programming languages like PHP.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew was written by Max Howell in 2009.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] In March 2013, Homebrew successfully completed a Kickstarter campaign to raise funds for servers to test and build formulae and managed to raise £14,859.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] On December 13, 2013, the Homebrew repository migrated from Howell's GitHub account to its own project account.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] In February 2015, due to downtime at SourceForge which resulted in binaries being unavailable, Homebrew moved their hosting to Bintray.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] On September 21, 2016, Homebrew version 1.0.0 was released.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] In January 2019, Linuxbrew was merged back into Homebrew, adding beta support for Linux and the Windows Subsystem for Linux to the Homebrew feature set.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] On February 2, 2019, Homebrew version 2.0.0 was released.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] On September 21, 2020, Homebrew version 2.5.2 was released with support for bottle taps (binary package repositories) via GitHub Releases.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] Version 3.0.0 was released almost exactly two years after 2.0.0, on February 5, 2021, and added official support for Macs with Apple silicon.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] As of February 2021, Homebrew is maintained by a team of 34 people.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] On April 12, 2021, Homebrew version 3.1.0 was released completing their migration of bottles (binary packages) to GitHub Packages before the May 1, 2021 shutdown of Bintray as previously announced by JFrog.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] On February 16, 2023, Homebrew version 4.0.0 was released which defaults to fetching Homebrew-maintained formulae from hosted JSON files rather than local Git-cloned taps.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew is written in the Ruby programming language and targets the version of Ruby that comes installed with the macOS operating system.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] By default, it is installed into `/usr/local` on Intel-based machines and `/opt/homebrew` on Apple silicon.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] The installation consists of a Git repository that enables users to update Homebrew by pulling an updated repository from GitHub.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] The package manager builds software from source using "formulae", Ruby scripts constructed with the Homebrew domain-specific language (DSL) for managing dependencies, downloading source files, and configuring and compiling software.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] Binary packages called "bottles" provide pre-built formulae with default options.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew does not honor the default privileges of `/usr/local`; directory ownership is changed from root with group permissions for the wheel group to the installing user and the "admin" group.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] Specifically, the mode changes from `drwxr-xr-x root wheel` to `drwxrwxr-x myuser admin`.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] All files, not just the directories, have their ownership changed by the installer.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] This is considered by some as a major security flaw.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew collects installation, build error, and operating system version statistics via InfluxDB.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] As of Homebrew 4.0.23, no data is collected via Google Analytics.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] Users can view analytics data from the last 30, 90, and 365 days on the Homebrew website.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] It is possible to opt out of data collection with the command `brew analytics off`.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] Homebrew typically supports macOS versions for which Apple still releases security updates, *i.e.*, the current major version of macOS as well as the two previous (major) versions.
[src:homebrew/homebrew-package-manager] As of June 2026 this included macOS 14 Sonoma, macOS 15 Sequoia, macOS 26 Tahoe, and MacOS 27 Golden Gate.
[src:homebrew/installation] Instructions for a supported install of Homebrew are on the homepage.
[src:homebrew/installation] The script installs Homebrew to its default, supported, best prefix (`/opt/homebrew` for Apple Silicon, `/usr/local` for macOS Intel and `/home/linuxbrew/.linuxbrew` for Linux) so that you don’t need *sudo* after Homebrew’s initial installation when you `brew install`.
[src:homebrew/installation] This prefix is required for most bottles (binary packages) to be used.
[src:homebrew/installation] It is a careful script; it can be run even if you have stuff installed in the preferred prefix already.
[src:homebrew/installation] It tells you exactly what it will do before it does it too.
[src:homebrew/installation] You have to confirm everything it will do before it starts.
[src:homebrew/installation] The macOS `.pkg` installer also installs Homebrew to its default prefix (`/opt/homebrew` for Apple Silicon and `/usr/local` for macOS Intel) for the same reasons as above.
[src:homebrew/installation] It’s available on Homebrew/brew’s latest GitHub release.
[src:homebrew/installation] To specify an alternate install user, like in situations where the package is installed at the login window before a user has logged in, write a property list file to `/var/tmp/.homebrew_pkg_user.plist` with the value `HOMEBREW_PKG_USER`.
[src:homebrew/installation] For example, `defaults write /var/tmp/.homebrew_pkg_user HOMEBREW_PKG_USER penny`.
[src:homebrew/installation] The file and user must exist prior to install.
[src:homebrew/installation] The Homebrew installer offers various advanced configuration settings.
[src:homebrew/installation] The default Git remote will be used if the corresponding environment variable is unset and works best for most users.
[src:homebrew/installation] This will make Homebrew install formulae and casks from the `homebrew/core` and `homebrew/cask` taps using local checkouts of these repositories instead of Homebrew’s API.
[src:homebrew/installation] Unless you are a Homebrew maintainer or contributor, you should probably not globally enable this setting.
[src:homebrew/installation] It can easily be enabled later after installation should it be necessary.
[src:homebrew/installation] If you want a non-interactive run of the Homebrew installer that doesn’t prompt for passwords (e.g. in automation scripts), prepend `NONINTERACTIVE=1` to the installation command.
[src:homebrew/installation] Check out the documentation for installing Homebrew on Linux.
[src:homebrew/installation] When you install Homebrew, it prints some directions for updating your shell’s config.
[src:homebrew/installation] If you don’t follow those directions, Homebrew will not work.
[src:homebrew/installation] Replace `<Homebrew prefix path>` with the directory where Homebrew is installed on your system.
[src:homebrew/installation] You can find Homebrew’s default install location in this FAQ entry.
[src:homebrew/installation] For more insight, re-run the installer or inspect the installer’s source to see how the installer constructs the path it recommends.
[src:homebrew/installation] See this tip in Tips and Tricks for another way to handle this across multiple operating systems.
[src:homebrew/installation] Uninstallation is documented in the FAQ.
[src:homebrew/installation] 1 For 32-bit or PPC support see MacPorts or Tigerbrew.
[src:homebrew/installation] 2 macOS 14 (Sonoma) or higher is best and supported, 10.15 (Catalina) – 13 (Ventura) are unsupported but may work and 10.14 (Mojave) and older will not run Homebrew at all.
[src:homebrew/installation] Using OpenCore Legacy Patcher is a Tier 2 or Tier 3 configuration depending on CPU generation.
[src:homebrew/installation] 3 You may need to install Xcode, the CLT, or both depending on the formula, to install a bottle (binary package) which is the only supported configuration.
[src:homebrew/installation] Downloading Xcode may require an Apple Developer account on older versions of Mac OS X.
[src:homebrew/installation] 4 The one-liner installation method found on brew.sh uses the Bourne-again shell at `/bin/bash`.
[src:homebrew/installation] Notably, `zsh`, `fish`, `tcsh` and `csh` will not work.
[src:homebrew/linux] There are many thousands of Linux distributions, many based directly or indirectly on other distributions; popular Linux distros include Debian, Fedora Linux, Linux Mint, Arch Linux, and Ubuntu, while commercial distributions include Red Hat Enterprise Linux, SUSE Linux Enterprise, and ChromeOS.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux distributions are frequently used in server platforms.
[src:homebrew/linux] Many Linux distributions use the word "**Linux**" in their name, but the Free Software Foundation uses and recommends the name "**GNU/Linux**", to emphasize the use and importance of GNU software in many distributions.
[src:homebrew/linux] Other than the Linux kernel, key components that make up a distribution may include a display server (windowing system), a package manager, a bootloader, and a Unix shell.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux is one of the most prominent examples of free and open-source software collaboration.
[src:homebrew/linux] The Linux kernel is considered by many to be the largest open source project.
[src:homebrew/linux] While originally developed for x86-based personal computers, it has since been ported to more platforms than any other operating system, and is used on a wide variety of devices including personal computers, workstations, mainframes, and embedded systems.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux is the predominant operating system for servers and is also used on all of the world's 500 fastest supercomputers.
[src:homebrew/linux] When combined with Android, which uses a Linux-based kernel and is designed for smartphones, they have the largest installed base of all general-purpose operating systems.
[src:homebrew/linux] The Linux kernel was created by Linus Torvalds, following the lack of a working kernel for GNU, a Unix-compatible operating system made entirely of free software that had been in development since 1983 by the GNU Project, led by Richard Stallman.
[src:homebrew/linux] A working Unix system called Minix was later released but its license was not entirely free at the time and it was made for education purposes.
[src:homebrew/linux] The first entirely free Unix for personal computers, 386BSD, did not appear until 1992, by which time Torvalds had already built and publicly released the first version of the Linux kernel on the Internet.
[src:homebrew/linux] Like GNU and 386BSD, Linux did not have any Unix code, being a fresh re-implementation, and therefore avoided legal issues from AT&T.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux distributions became popular in the 1990s and made Unix technologies accessible to home users on personal computers whereas previously it had been confined to sophisticated workstations.
[src:homebrew/linux] Desktop Linux distributions include a windowing system such as X11 or Wayland and a desktop environment such as KDE Plasma, GNOME, or Xfce.
[src:homebrew/linux] Distributions intended for servers may not have a graphical user interface at all or include a solution stack such as LAMP.
[src:homebrew/linux] The source code of Linux may be used, modified, and distributed commercially or non-commercially by anyone under the terms of its respective licenses, such as the GNU General Public License (GPL).
[src:homebrew/linux] The license means creating novel distributions is permitted by anyone and is easier than it would be for an operating system such as macOS or Microsoft Windows.
[src:homebrew/linux] The Linux kernel, for example, is licensed under the GPLv2, with an exception for system calls that allows code that calls the kernel via system calls not to be licensed under the GPL.
[src:homebrew/linux] Because of the dominance of Linux-based Android on smartphones, Linux, including Android, has the largest installed base of all general-purpose operating systems as of May 2022.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux is, as of March 2024, used by around 4 percent of desktop computers.
[src:homebrew/linux] The Chromebook, which runs the Linux kernel-based ChromeOS, dominates the US K–12 education market and represents nearly 20 percent of sub-$300 notebook sales in the US.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux also runs on embedded systems, i.e., devices whose operating system is typically built into the firmware and is highly tailored to the system.
[src:homebrew/linux] This includes routers, automation controls, smart home devices, video game consoles, televisions (Samsung and LG smart TVs), automobiles (Tesla, Audi, Mercedes-Benz, Hyundai, and Toyota), and spacecraft (Falcon 9 rocket, Dragon crew capsule, and the Ingenuity Mars helicopter).
[src:homebrew/linux] The Unix operating system was conceived of and implemented in 1969, at AT&T's Bell Labs in the United States, by Ken Thompson, Dennis Ritchie, Douglas McIlroy, and Joe Ossanna.
[src:homebrew/linux] First released in 1971, Unix was written entirely in assembly language, as was common practice at the time.
[src:homebrew/linux] In 1973, in a key pioneering approach, it was rewritten in the C programming language by Dennis Ritchie (except for some hardware and I/O routines).
[src:homebrew/linux] The availability of a high-level language implementation of Unix made its porting to different computer platforms easier.
[src:homebrew/linux] As a 1956 antitrust case forbade AT&T from entering the computer business, AT&T provided the operating system's source code to anyone who asked.
[src:homebrew/linux] As a result, Unix use grew quickly and it became widely adopted by academic institutions and businesses.
[src:homebrew/linux] In 1984, AT&T divested itself of its regional operating companies, and was released from its obligation not to enter the computer business; freed of that obligation, Bell Labs began selling Unix as a proprietary product, where users were not legally allowed to modify it.
[src:homebrew/linux] Onyx Systems began selling early microcomputer-based Unix workstations in 1980.
[src:homebrew/linux] Later, Sun Microsystems, founded as a spin-off of a student project at Stanford University, also began selling Unix-based desktop workstations in 1982.
[src:homebrew/linux] While Sun workstations did not use commodity PC hardware, for which Linux was later originally developed, it represented the first successful commercial attempt at distributing a primarily single-user microcomputer that ran a Unix operating system.
[src:homebrew/linux] With Unix increasingly "locked in" as a proprietary product, the GNU Project, started in 1983 by Richard Stallman, had the goal of creating a "complete Unix-compatible software system" composed entirely of free software.
[src:homebrew/linux] Later, in 1985, Stallman started the Free Software Foundation and wrote the GNU General Public License (GNU GPL) in 1989.
[src:homebrew/linux] Tanenbaum, a computer science professor, and released in 1987 as a minimal Unix-like operating system targeted at students and others who wanted to learn operating system principles.
[src:homebrew/linux] Although the complete source code of Minix was freely available, the licensing terms prevented it from being free software until the licensing changed in April 2000.
[src:homebrew/linux] While attending the University of Helsinki in the fall of 1990, Torvalds enrolled in a Unix course.
[src:homebrew/linux] The course used a MicroVAX minicomputer running Ultrix, and one of the required texts was *Operating Systems: Design and Implementation* by Andrew S.
[src:homebrew/linux] This textbook included a copy of Tanenbaum's Minix operating system.
[src:homebrew/linux] It was with this course that Torvalds first became exposed to Unix.
[src:homebrew/linux] In 1991, he became curious about operating systems.
[src:homebrew/linux] Frustrated by the licensing of Minix, which at the time limited it to educational use only, he began to work on his operating system kernel, which eventually became the Linux kernel.
[src:homebrew/linux] On 3 July 1991, to implement Unix system calls, Linus Torvalds attempted unsuccessfully to obtain a digital copy of the POSIX standards documentation with a request to the *comp.os.minix* newsgroup.
[src:homebrew/linux] After not finding the POSIX documentation, Torvalds initially resorted to determining system calls from SunOS documentation owned by the university for use in operating its Sun Microsystems server.
[src:homebrew/linux] He also learned some system calls from Tanenbaum's Minix text.
[src:homebrew/linux] Torvalds began the development of the Linux kernel on Minix and applications written for Minix were also used on Linux.
[src:homebrew/linux] Later, Linux matured and further Linux kernel development took place on Linux systems.
[src:homebrew/linux] Torvalds initiated a switch from his original license, which prohibited commercial redistribution, to the GNU GPL.
[src:homebrew/linux] Developers worked to integrate GNU components with the Linux kernel, creating a fully functional and free operating system.
[src:homebrew/linux] Although not released until 1992, due to legal complications, the development of 386BSD, from which NetBSD, OpenBSD and FreeBSD descended, predated that of Linux.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linus Torvalds has stated that if the GNU kernel or 386BSD had been available in 1991, he probably would not have created Linux.
[src:homebrew/linux] The Linux kernel is licensed under the GNU General Public License (GPL), version 2.
[src:homebrew/linux] The GPL requires that anyone who distributes software based on source code under this license must make the originating source code (and any modifications) available to the recipient under the same terms.
[src:homebrew/linux] Torvalds states that the Linux kernel will not move from version 2 of the GPL to version 3.
[src:homebrew/linux] He specifically dislikes some provisions in the new license which prohibit the use of the software in digital rights management.
[src:homebrew/linux] It would also be impractical to obtain permission from all the copyright holders, who number in the thousands.
[src:homebrew/linux] A 2001 study of Red Hat Linux 7.1 found that this distribution contained 30 million lines of source code.
[src:homebrew/linux] Using the Constructive Cost Model, the study estimated that this distribution required about eight thousand person-years of development time.
[src:homebrew/linux] According to the study, if all this software had been developed by conventional proprietary means, it would have cost about US$1.86 billion to develop in 2024 in the United States.
[src:homebrew/linux] Most of the source code (71%) was written in the C programming language, but many other languages were used, including C++, Lisp, assembly language, Perl, Python, Fortran, and various shell scripting languages.
[src:homebrew/linux] Slightly over half of all lines of code were licensed under the GPL.
[src:homebrew/linux] The Linux kernel itself was 2.4 million lines of code, or 8% of the total.
[src:homebrew/linux] In a later study, the same analysis was performed for Debian version 4.0 (etch, which was released in 2007).
[src:homebrew/linux] This distribution contained close to 283 million lines of source code, and the study estimated that it would have required about seventy three thousand man-years and cost US$10.4 billion (in 2024 dollars) to develop by conventional means.
[src:homebrew/linux] In the United States, the name *Linux* is a trademark registered to Linus Torvalds.
[src:homebrew/linux] Della Croce Jr. filed for the trademark *Linux*, and then demanded royalties from Linux distributors.
[src:homebrew/linux] In 1996, Torvalds and some affected organizations sued him to have the trademark assigned to Torvalds, and, in 1997, the case was settled.
[src:homebrew/linux] The licensing of the trademark has since been handled by the Linux Mark Institute (LMI).
[src:homebrew/linux] Torvalds has stated that he trademarked the name only to prevent someone else from using it.
[src:homebrew/linux] LMI originally charged a nominal sublicensing fee for use of the Linux name as part of trademarks, but later changed this in favor of offering a free, perpetual worldwide sublicense.
[src:homebrew/linux] The Free Software Foundation (FSF) prefers *GNU/Linux* as the name when referring to the operating system as a whole, because it considers Linux distributions to be variants of the GNU operating system initiated in 1983 by Richard Stallman, president of the FSF.
[src:homebrew/linux] The foundation explicitly takes no issue over the name Android for the Android OS, which is also an operating system based on the Linux kernel, as GNU is not a part of it.
[src:homebrew/linux] A minority of public figures and software projects other than Stallman and the FSF, notably distributions consisting of only free software, such as Debian (which had been sponsored by the FSF up to 1996), also use *GNU/Linux* when referring to the operating system as a whole.
[src:homebrew/linux] Most media and common usage, however, refers to this family of operating systems simply as *Linux*, as do many large Linux distributions (for example, SUSE Linux and Red Hat Enterprise Linux).
[src:homebrew/linux] As of May 2011, about 8% to 13% of the lines of code of the Linux distribution Ubuntu (version "Natty") is made of GNU components (the range depending on whether GNOME is considered part of GNU); meanwhile, 6% is taken by the Linux kernel, increased to 9% when including its direct dependencies.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linus Torvalds had wanted to call his invention "Freax", a portmanteau of "free", "freak", and "x" (as an allusion to Unix).
[src:homebrew/linux] During the start of his work on the system, some of the project's makefiles included the name "Freax" for about half a year.
[src:homebrew/linux] Torvalds considered the name "Linux" but dismissed it as too egotistical.
[src:homebrew/linux] To facilitate development, the files were uploaded to the FTP server of FUNET in September 1991.
[src:homebrew/linux] Ari Lemmke, Torvalds' coworker at the Helsinki University of Technology (HUT) who was one of the volunteer administrators for the FTP server at the time, did not think that "Freax" was a good name, so he named the project "Linux" on the server without consulting Torvalds.
[src:homebrew/linux] Later, however, Torvalds consented to "Linux".
[src:homebrew/linux] According to a newsgroup post by Torvalds, the word "Linux" should be pronounced (/ˈlɪnʊks/ ⓘ *LIN-uuks*) with a short 'i' as in 'print' and 'u' as in 'put'.
[src:homebrew/linux] To further demonstrate how the word "Linux" should be pronounced, he included an audio guide with the kernel source code.
[src:homebrew/linux] However, in this recording, he pronounces Linux as */ˈlinʊks/* (*LEEN-uuks*) with a short but close front unrounded vowel, instead of a near-close near-front unrounded vowel as in his newsgroup post.
[src:homebrew/linux] Commercial use began when Dell and IBM, followed by Hewlett-Packard, started offering Linux support to escape Microsoft's monopoly in the desktop operating system market.
[src:homebrew/linux] Today, Linux systems are used throughout computing, from embedded systems to virtually all supercomputers, and have secured a place in server installations such as the popular LAMP application stack.
[src:homebrew/linux] The use of Linux distributions in home and enterprise desktops has been growing.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux distributions have also become popular in the netbook market, with many devices shipping with customized Linux distributions installed, and Google releasing their own ChromeOS designed for netbooks.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux's greatest success in the consumer market is perhaps the mobile device market, with Android being the dominant operating system on smartphones and very popular on tablets and, more recently, on wearables, and vehicles.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux gaming is also on the rise with Valve showing its support for Linux and rolling out SteamOS, its own gaming-oriented Linux distribution, which was later implemented in their Steam Deck platform.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux distributions have also gained popularity with various local and national governments, such as the federal government of Brazil.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linus Torvalds is the lead maintainer for the Linux kernel and guides its development, while Greg Kroah-Hartman is the lead maintainer for the stable branch.
[src:homebrew/linux] Zoë Kooyman is the executive director of the Free Software Foundation, which in turn supports the GNU components.
[src:homebrew/linux] Finally, individuals and corporations develop third-party non-GNU components.
[src:homebrew/linux] These third-party components comprise a vast body of work and may include both kernel modules and user applications and libraries.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux vendors and communities combine and distribute the kernel, GNU components, and non-GNU components, with additional package management software in the form of Linux distributions.
[src:homebrew/linux] Many quantitative studies of free/open-source software focus on topics including market share and reliability, with numerous studies specifically examining Linux.
[src:homebrew/linux] The Linux market is growing, and the Linux operating system market size is expected to see a growth of 19.2% by 2027, reaching $15.64 billion, compared to $3.89 billion in 2019.
[src:homebrew/linux] Analysts project a Compound Annual Growth Rate (CAGR) of 13.7% between 2024 and 2032, culminating in a market size of US$34.90 billion by the latter year.
[src:homebrew/linux] Analysts and proponents attribute the relative success of Linux to its security, reliability, low cost, and freedom from vendor lock-in.
[src:homebrew/linux] estimate that 96.55% of web servers run Linux, 1.73% run Windows, and 1.72% run FreeBSD.
[src:homebrew/linux] this estimate was based on the number of Linux servers sold by various companies, and did not include server hardware purchased separately that had Linux installed on it later.
[src:homebrew/linux] As of 2024, estimates suggest Linux accounts for at least 80% of the public cloud workload, partly thanks to its widespread use in platforms like Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud Platform.
[src:homebrew/linux] ZDNet reports that 96.3% of the top one million web servers are running Linux.
[src:homebrew/linux] W3Techs states that Linux powers at least 39.2% of websites whose operating system is known, with other estimates saying 55%.
[src:homebrew/linux] Android, which is based on the Linux kernel, has become the dominant operating system for smartphones.
[src:homebrew/linux] holding 28%, and the remaining 1% attributed to various niche platforms.
[src:homebrew/linux] For years, Linux has been the platform of choice in the film industry.
[src:homebrew/linux] According to the Linux Movies Group, more than 95% of the servers and desktops at large animation and visual effects companies use Linux.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux distributions have also gained popularity with various local and national governments.
[src:homebrew/linux] News of the Russian military creating its own Linux distribution has also surfaced, and has come to fruition as the G.H.ost Project.
[src:homebrew/linux] has gone to the extent of mandating that all state high schools run Linux on their computers.
[src:homebrew/linux] processor family to achieve technology independence.
[src:homebrew/linux] In Spain, some regions have developed their own Linux distributions, which are widely used in education and official institutions, like gnuLinEx in Extremadura and Guadalinex in Andalusia.
[src:homebrew/linux] have also taken steps toward the adoption of Linux.
[src:homebrew/linux] In April 2026 France ordered its ministries to begin to replace 2.5 million Windows desktops with Linux.
[src:homebrew/linux] , is based on a version of Fedora Linux.
[src:homebrew/linux] Many developers of open-source software agree that the Linux kernel was not designed but rather evolved through natural selection.
[src:homebrew/linux] Torvalds considers that although the design of Unix served as a scaffolding, "Linux grew with a lot of mutations – and because the mutations were less than random, they were faster and more directed than alpha-particles in DNA." Eric S.
[src:homebrew/linux] Raymond considers Linux's revolutionary aspects to be social, not technical: before Linux, complex software was designed carefully by small groups, but "Linux evolved in a completely different way.
[src:homebrew/linux] From nearly the beginning, it was rather casually hacked on by huge numbers of volunteers coordinating only through the Internet.
[src:homebrew/linux] A Linux-based system is a modular Unix-like operating system, deriving much of its basic design from principles established in Unix during the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:homebrew/linux] Such a system uses a monolithic kernel, the Linux kernel, which handles process control, networking, access to the peripherals, and file systems.
[src:homebrew/linux] Device drivers are either integrated directly with the kernel or added as modules that are loaded while the system is running.
[src:homebrew/linux] The GNU userland is a key part of most systems based on the Linux kernel, with Android being a notable exception.
[src:homebrew/linux] The GNU Project also develops Bash, a popular CLI shell.
[src:homebrew/linux] The graphical user interface (or GUI) used by most Linux systems is built on top of an implementation of the X Window System.
[src:homebrew/linux] More recently, some of the Linux community has sought to move to using Wayland as the display server protocol, replacing X11.
[src:homebrew/linux] Many other open-source software projects contribute to Linux systems.
[src:homebrew/linux] The user interface, also known as the shell, is either a command-line interface (CLI), a graphical user interface (GUI), or controls attached to the associated hardware, which is common for embedded systems.
[src:homebrew/linux] For desktop systems, the default user interface is usually graphical, although the CLI is commonly available through terminal emulator windows or on a separate virtual console.
[src:homebrew/linux] CLI shells are text-based user interfaces, which use text for both input and output.
[src:homebrew/linux] The dominant shell used in Linux is the Bourne-Again Shell (bash), originally developed for the GNU Project; other shells such as Zsh are also used.
[src:homebrew/linux] Most low-level Linux components, including various parts of the userland, use the CLI exclusively.
[src:homebrew/linux] The CLI is particularly suited for automation of repetitive or delayed tasks and provides very simple inter-process communication.
[src:homebrew/linux] On desktop systems, the most popular user interfaces are the GUI shells, packaged together with extensive desktop environments, such as KDE Plasma, GNOME, MATE, Cinnamon, LXDE, Pantheon, and Xfce, though a variety of additional user interfaces exist.
[src:homebrew/linux] Most popular user interfaces are based on the X Window System, often simply called "X" or "X11".
[src:homebrew/linux] It provides network transparency and permits a graphical application running on one system to be displayed on another where a user may interact with the application; however, certain extensions of the X Window System are not capable of working over the network.
[src:homebrew/linux] Several X display servers exist, with the reference implementation, X.Org Server, being the most popular.
[src:homebrew/linux] Several types of window managers exist for X11, including tiling, dynamic, stacking, and compositing.
[src:homebrew/linux] Window managers provide means to control the placement and appearance of individual application windows, and interact with the X Window System.
[src:homebrew/linux] Desktop environments include window managers as part of their standard installations, such as Mutter (GNOME), KWin (KDE), or Xfwm (xfce), although users may choose to use a different window manager if preferred.
[src:homebrew/linux] Wayland is a display server protocol intended as a replacement for the X11 protocol; as of 2022, it has received relatively wide adoption.
[src:homebrew/linux] Unlike X11, Wayland does not need an external window manager and compositing manager.
[src:homebrew/linux] Therefore, a Wayland compositor takes the role of the display server, window manager, and compositing manager.
[src:homebrew/linux] Weston is the reference implementation of Wayland, while GNOME's Mutter and KDE's KWin are being ported to Wayland as standalone display servers.
[src:homebrew/linux] Enlightenment has already been successfully ported since version 19.
[src:homebrew/linux] Additionally, many window managers have been made for Wayland, such as Sway or Hyprland, as well as other graphical utilities such as Waybar or Rofi.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux currently has two modern kernel-userspace APIs for handling video input devices: V4L2 API for video streams and radio, and DVB API for digital TV reception.
[src:homebrew/linux] The diversity of hardware standards and data formats requires continuous architectural refinement to maintain compatibility across different device classes.
[src:homebrew/linux] Development focuses on providing robust userspace libraries to abstract device complexity, ensuring that applications can interface with varying formats without specialized hardware-specific drivers.
[src:homebrew/linux] The primary difference between Linux and many other popular contemporary operating systems is that the Linux kernel and other components are free and open-source software.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux is not the only such operating system, although it is by far the most widely used.
[src:homebrew/linux] Some free and open-source software licenses are based on the principle of copyleft, a kind of reciprocity: any work derived from a copyleft piece of software must also be copyleft itself.
[src:homebrew/linux] The most common free software license, the GNU General Public License (GPL), is a form of copyleft and is used for the Linux kernel and many of the components from the GNU Project.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux-based distributions are intended by developers for interoperability with other operating systems and established computing standards.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux systems adhere to POSIX, Single UNIX Specification (SUS), Linux Standard Base (LSB), ISO, and ANSI standards where possible, although to date only one Linux distribution has been POSIX.1 certified, Linux-FT.
[src:homebrew/linux] The Open Group has tested and certified at least two Linux distributions as qualifying for the Unix trademark, EulerOS and Inspur K-UX.
[src:homebrew/linux] Free software projects, although developed through collaboration, are often produced independently of each other.
[src:homebrew/linux] The fact that the software licenses explicitly permit redistribution, however, provides a basis for larger-scale projects that collect the software produced by stand-alone projects and make it available all at once in the form of a Linux distribution.
[src:homebrew/linux] Many Linux distributions manage a remote collection of system software and application software packages available for download and installation through a network connection.
[src:homebrew/linux] This allows users to adapt the operating system to their specific needs.
[src:homebrew/linux] Distributions are maintained by individuals, loose-knit teams, volunteer organizations, and commercial entities.
[src:homebrew/linux] A distribution is responsible for the default configuration of the installed Linux kernel, general system security, and more generally integration of the different software packages into a coherent whole.
[src:homebrew/linux] Distributions typically use a package manager such as apt, yum, zypper, pacman or portage to install, remove, and update all of a system's software from one central location.
[src:homebrew/linux] A distribution is largely driven by its developer and user communities.
[src:homebrew/linux] Some vendors develop and fund their distributions on a volunteer basis, Debian being a well-known example.
[src:homebrew/linux] Others maintain a community version of their commercial distributions, as Red Hat does with Fedora, and SUSE does with openSUSE.
[src:homebrew/linux] In many cities and regions, local associations known as Linux User Groups (LUGs) seek to promote their preferred distribution and by extension free software.
[src:homebrew/linux] They hold meetings and provide free demonstrations, training, technical support, and operating system installation to new users.
[src:homebrew/linux] Many Internet communities also provide support to Linux users and developers.
[src:homebrew/linux] Most distributions and free software / open-source projects have IRC chatrooms or newsgroups.
[src:homebrew/linux] Online forums are another means of support, with notable examples being Unix & Linux Stack Exchange, LinuxQuestions.org and the various distribution-specific support and community forums, such as ones for Ubuntu, Fedora, Arch Linux, Gentoo, etc.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux distributions host mailing lists; commonly there will be a specific topic such as usage or development for a given list.
[src:homebrew/linux] There are several technology websites with a Linux focus.
[src:homebrew/linux] Print magazines on Linux often bundle cover disks that carry software or even complete Linux distributions.
[src:homebrew/linux] Although Linux distributions are generally available without charge, several large corporations sell, support, and contribute to the development of the components of the system and free software.
[src:homebrew/linux] An analysis of the Linux kernel in 2017 showed that well over 85% of the code was developed by programmers who are being paid for their work, leaving about 8.2% to unpaid developers and 4.1% unclassified.
[src:homebrew/linux] Some of the major corporations that provide contributions include Intel, Samsung, Google, AMD, Oracle, and Facebook.
[src:homebrew/linux] Several corporations, notably Red Hat, Canonical, and SUSE have built a significant business around Linux distributions.
[src:homebrew/linux] The free software licenses, on which the various software packages of a distribution built on the Linux kernel are based, explicitly accommodate and encourage commercialization; the relationship between a Linux distribution as a whole and individual vendors may be seen as symbiotic.
[src:homebrew/linux] One common business model of commercial suppliers is charging for support, especially for business users.
[src:homebrew/linux] A number of companies also offer a specialized business version of their distribution, which adds proprietary support packages and tools to administer higher numbers of installations or to simplify administrative tasks.
[src:homebrew/linux] Another business model is to give away the software to sell hardware.
[src:homebrew/linux] This used to be the norm in the computer industry, with operating systems such as CP/M, Apple DOS, and versions of the classic Mac OS before 7.6 freely copyable (but not modifiable).
[src:homebrew/linux] As computer hardware standardized throughout the 1980s, it became more difficult for hardware manufacturers to profit from this tactic, as the OS would run on any manufacturer's computer that shared the same architecture.
[src:homebrew/linux] Most programming languages support Linux either directly or through third-party community based ports.
[src:homebrew/linux] The original development tools used for building both Linux applications and operating system programs are found within the GNU toolchain, which includes the GNU Compiler Collection (GCC) and the GNU Build System.
[src:homebrew/linux] Among others, GCC provides compilers for Ada, C, C++, Go and Fortran.
[src:homebrew/linux] Many programming languages have a cross-platform reference implementation that supports Linux, for example PHP, Perl, Ruby, Python, Java, Go, Rust and Haskell.
[src:homebrew/linux] First released in 2003, the LLVM project provides an alternative cross-platform open-source compiler for many languages.
[src:homebrew/linux] Proprietary compilers for Linux include the Intel C++ Compiler, Sun Studio, and IBM XL C/C++ Compiler.
[src:homebrew/linux] BASIC is available in procedural form from QB64, PureBasic, Yabasic, GLBasic, Basic4GL, XBasic, wxBasic, SdlBasic, and Basic-256, and in object oriented through Gambas, FreeBASIC, B4X, Basic for Qt, Phoenix Object Basic, NS Basic, ProvideX, Chipmunk Basic, RapidQ and Xojo.
[src:homebrew/linux] Pascal is implemented through GNU Pascal, Free Pascal, Virtual Pascal, and graphically via Lazarus, PascalABC.NET, or Delphi using FireMonkey (formerly through Borland Kylix).
[src:homebrew/linux] A common feature of Unix-like systems, Linux includes traditional specific-purpose programming languages targeted at scripting, text processing and system configuration and management in general.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux distributions support shell scripts, AWK, sed and make.
[src:homebrew/linux] Many programs also have an embedded programming language to support configuring or programming themselves.
[src:homebrew/linux] For example, regular expressions are supported in programs like grep and locate, the traditional Unix message transfer agent Sendmail contains its own Turing complete scripting system, and the advanced text editor GNU Emacs is built around a general purpose Lisp interpreter.
[src:homebrew/linux] Most distributions also include support for PHP, Perl, Ruby, Python and other dynamic languages.
[src:homebrew/linux] While not as common, Linux also supports C# and other CLI languages (via Mono), Vala, and Scheme.
[src:homebrew/linux] Many Java virtual machines and development kits run on Linux, including the original Sun Microsystems JVM (HotSpot), IBM's J2SE RE, and many open-source projects like Kaffe and Jikes RVM; Kotlin, Scala, Groovy and other JVM languages are also available.
[src:homebrew/linux] GNOME and KDE are popular desktop environments and provide a framework for developing applications.
[src:homebrew/linux] These projects are based on the GTK and Qt widget toolkits, respectively, which can also be used independently of the larger framework.
[src:homebrew/linux] Both support a wide variety of languages.
[src:homebrew/linux] There are a number of Integrated development environments available including Anjuta, Code::Blocks, CodeLite, Eclipse, Geany, ActiveState Komodo, KDevelop, Lazarus, MonoDevelop, NetBeans, and Qt Creator, while the long-established editors Vim, nano and Emacs remain popular.
[src:homebrew/linux] A topic of perennial discussion is the area of graphic design on Linux.
[src:homebrew/linux] Typical common graphics and image tools are programs such as: GNU Image Manipulation Program (GIMP), Inkscape, Krita, DaVinci Resolve, and Scribus.
[src:homebrew/linux] The Linux kernel is a widely ported operating system kernel, available for devices ranging from mobile phones to supercomputers; it runs on a highly diverse range of computer architectures, including ARM-based Android smartphones and the IBM Z mainframes.
[src:homebrew/linux] Specialized distributions and kernel forks exist for less mainstream architectures; for example, the ELKS kernel fork can run on Intel 8086 or Intel 80286 16-bit microprocessors, while the μClinux kernel fork may run on systems without a memory management unit.
[src:homebrew/linux] The kernel also runs on architectures that were only ever intended to use a proprietary manufacturer-created operating system, such as Macintosh computers (with PowerPC, Intel, and Apple silicon processors), PDAs, video game consoles, portable music players, and mobile phones.
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux has a reputation for supporting old hardware very well by maintaining standardized drivers for a long time.
[src:homebrew/linux] There are several industry associations and hardware conferences devoted to maintaining and improving support for diverse hardware under Linux, such as FreedomHEC.
[src:homebrew/linux] Over time, support for different hardware has improved in Linux, resulting in any off-the-shelf purchase having a "good chance" of being compatible.
[src:homebrew/linux] In 2014, a new initiative was launched to automatically collect a database of all tested hardware configurations.
[src:homebrew/linux] One commonly expressed attribute about Linux (or open source software in general) is that through regular vetting by many individuals the software is progressively made more secure, a process referred to as being called "Linus's law".
[src:homebrew/linux] Linux is often highlighted for its share of the estimated global servers market share.
[src:homebrew/linux] Besides many volunteers, the not-for-profit bodies such as the Open Source Security Foundation and Linux Foundation actively pursue ways to promote security in the Linux platform as well.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:homebrew/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:homebrew/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
